{"id":"1702.08625","submitter":"Xiyun Zhang","authors":"Wenwen Huang, Xiyun Zhang, Xin Hu, Zonghua Liu, and Shuguang Guan","title":"Fluctuation of Dynamical Robustness in a Networked Oscillators System","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.4881215","report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.AO physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this work, we study the dynamical robustness in a system consisting of\nboth active and inactive oscillators. We analytically show that the dynamical\nrobustness of such system is determined by the cross link density between\nactive and inactive subpopulations, which depends on the specific process of\ninactivation. It is the multi-valued dependence of the cross link density on\nthe control parameter, i.e., the ratio of inactive oscillators in the system,\nthat leads to the fluctuation of the critical points. We further investigate\nhow different network topologies and inactivation strategies affect the\nfluctuation. Our results explain why the fluctuation is more obvious in\nheterogeneous networks than in homogeneous ones, and why the low-degree nodes\nare crucial in terms of dynamical robustness. The analytical results are\nsupported by numerical verifications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 28 Feb 2017 03:15:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-03-01"}
